This report documents results of traffic analyses conducted in conjunction with the proposed
Street roadway improvement project in Lincoln, Nebraska. The study limits include the
Street corridor from north of the I-80 interchange to U.S. Highway 34 (US-34). The US-
to W Mathis Road are also included in this study. A map showing the general location of the
project and the study intersections for this analysis is illustrated in Figure 1.
The purpose of the traffic analysis was to establish typical roadway cross-sections and
determine geometric and traffic control needs along the NW 48
Street study corridors that will provide adequate capacity for existing traffic conditions and future
horizon year (2040) conditions. Both existing traffic conditions and future year (2040) traffic
conditions were evaluated in this study. An access management review was performed to
determine potential improvements to intersection alignment, access spacing, and intersection

Based on the existing traffic volumes, nine intersections were evaluated for signalization
warrants. The Manual on Uniform Traffic Control Devices, 2009 Edition (MUTCD) provides nine
signal warrants for evaluation of signalization at intersections. The preliminary need for
signalization was based on the Four-Hour Vehicular Volume Warrant (Warrant 2) and the Peak
Hour Volume Warrant (Warrant 3) contained in the MUTCD. The Eight-Hour Vehicular Volume
Warrant (Warrant 1) was not evaluated due to the absence of thorough 24-hour traffic volume
data on minor streets in the study area. Other MUTCD signal warrants include reviews of
pedestrians, crash experience, traffic progression, and at-grade railroad crossings. These traffic
signal warrants were either not expected to be satisfied at any location in the study area or were
not evaluated due to insufficient data.
The National Cooperative Highway Research Program (NCHRP) Report 457 provides guidance
as to how right-turn volumes should be utilized in the evaluation of signal warrants. Vehicles
making right-turns from minor approaches at unsignalized intersections experience less delay
than vehicles making left-turns or crossing through the intersection. Therefore, intersections
with high right-turn volumes may not benefit from signalization as much as intersections with
high left-turn and through volumes. For the purposes of this study, the methodologies in
NCHRP Report 457 were used as guidance in determining the reduction in right-turn volumes
from the minor approach for the evaluation of the peak hour signal warrants. Results of the
peak hour signal warrant analysis indicate that three of the unsignalized study intersections
satisfy either the AM or the PM peak hour signal warrant; however, none of the unsignalized
intersections currently satisfy both AM and PM peak hour warrants. Three intersections satisfy
the Four-Hour Volume signal warrant: NW 48
Knight Drive, and US-34 & Airport Road.
